under the collapsed trachea.

175
00:07:00,754 --> 00:07:02,824
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

176
00:07:04,558 --> 00:07:07,628
Starting high flow O2.

177
00:07:07,661 --> 00:07:10,661
[ Beeping continues ]

178
00:07:10,698 --> 00:07:12,568
[ Beeping slows ]

179
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:14,130
And we're good.

180
00:07:14,167 --> 00:07:15,037
[ Sighs ]

181
00:07:15,068 --> 00:07:17,708
Now that our patient
is actually breathing,

182
00:07:17,738 --> 00:07:19,168
we can realign
and repair.

183
00:07:19,206 --> 00:07:20,966
Four-O on a driver.

184
00:07:21,008 --> 00:07:23,478
Scissors.
Sponge stick.

185
00:07:25,779 --> 00:07:27,979
It's a slippery thing letting
your feelings about a patient

186
00:07:28,015 --> 00:07:30,815
influence
your medical judgment.

187
00:07:30,851 --> 00:07:32,021
I didn't.

188
00:07:32,052 --> 00:07:34,152
I get the instinct --
She's a victim.

189
00:07:34,187 --> 00:07:35,817
He's a shooter,
a racist.

190
00:07:35,856 --> 00:07:37,786
Often we don't even know
we're doing it.

191
00:07:37,825 --> 00:07:39,555
I would never
let my personal feelings

192
00:07:39,593 --> 00:07:40,733
impact
a patient's care.

193
00:07:40,761 --> 00:07:41,931
She was bleeding out.

194
00:07:41,962 --> 00:07:44,132
And this guy just drew his first
good breath 30 seconds ago.

195
00:07:44,164 --> 00:07:45,534
They were both critical!

196
00:07:45,566 --> 00:07:47,266
He was dying.
You were wrong. Own it.

197
00:07:47,300 --> 00:07:48,270
[ Scoffs ]

198
00:07:48,301 --> 00:07:49,541
You know
as well as I do that

199
00:07:49,570 --> 00:07:50,770
that was not
an easy call to make.

200
00:07:50,804 --> 00:07:51,944
Do I?
Yes!

201
00:07:51,972 --> 00:07:55,182
**

202
00:07:56,744 --> 00:07:58,984
Clear the field,
Dr. Browne.

